{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Primary/Secondary TNs fine, but not \"Ultimate\" for Zeroth",
    "content": "Mixed. Two are fine, one is still problematic.\n\n**\"Primary Reality\" as TN for First Reality -- fine.** \"Primary\" in English means \"first in order, fundamental starting point.\" This accurately glosses the author's intent: phenomena are where we begin. No ontological overreach, just a restatement of the ordinal in a more descriptive register.\n\n**\"Secondary Reality\" as TN for Second Reality -- fine in a footnote.** In a TN, \"secondary\" reads as \"derived from the primary\" rather than \"lesser.\" The footnote context neutralizes the evaluative connotation because the reader has already absorbed the ordinal name as the real term. The TN just says: \"this is the layer built upon the first.\"\n\n**\"Ultimate Reality\" as TN for Zeroth Reality -- still problematic.** Even in a footnote, \"Ultimate Reality\" is a loaded term with centuries of metaphysical baggage. The reader who sees \"TN: Ultimate Reality\" will hear Brahman, God, the Absolute, Kant's noumenon -- exactly the entities the author argues are unreachable constructions. The author's Zeroth Reality is the *hypothetical ground beneath phenomena* that, when posited, immediately becomes Second Reality (footnote 15: \"when we propose the Zeroth Reality, what we propose IS Second Reality\"). Glossing it as \"Ultimate Reality\" makes it sound like the author believes in such a ground, when the whole point is that it is structurally inaccessible.\n\n**Alternative TN for Zeroth Reality:** \"the hypothetical ground\" or \"the posited ground\" -- something that signals its status as a construct that cannot be accessed, rather than a metaphysical ultimate that anchors everything. Or simply: \"TN: what traditional metaphysics calls 'ultimate reality' (终极实在), which the author argues is structurally inaccessible.\" This preserves the connection to the tradition without endorsing the term."
  }
}
